). In particular, mogroside V (MV) has attracted great interest for its low calorie content and high sweetness and is widely used as a natural sweetener in the food and beverage industry (B. Wang et al., 2019). The sweetness of MV is approximately 300-fold that of sucrose. In addition to being used in folk medicine, mogrosides have several kinds of pharmacological characteristics, including anticancer (

), anti-hyperglycaemic (

), antioxidative (

), anti-inflammatory (

) and antidiabetic (

) properties. To date, the mogroside biosynthesis pathway has been completely elucidated (Itkin et al., 2016), and a comprehensive 

S. grosvenorii

reference genome is available (

), facilitating functional gene characterization and genetic improvement. The bulk of enzymes and coding genes responsible for the biosynthesis of mogrosides have been successfully cloned, including squalene epoxidases (Itkin et al., 2016), cucurbitadienol synthase (

), epoxide hydrolases (Itkin et al., 2016), cytochrome P450 mono-oxygenase (
CYP
450) (

), NADPH-cytochrome P450 reductases (CPRs) (

), and UDP-glucosyltransferases (

), which are generally identified in microorganisms. Therefore, it is essential to further identify gene function in 

S. grosvenorii

