CYP 450 is responsible for the C3, C11, C24 and C25 hydroxylation required to produce mogrol in the mogroside biosynthesis pathway (Itkin et al., 2016), and CPRs are the essential partners (
) ( Fig. 1 ). Plant CYP 450 enzyme function is performed along with CPR function, representing pivotal factors in the conversion of NADPH to electrons via flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD) and flavin mononucleotide (FMN) to CYP 450 (with a haem-iron group) (
;
). In recent years, various CPRs have been cloned and characterized. Three CPR genes were found in
A. thaliana
, among which the ATR1 and ATR2 genes encoded the active domain of CPRs, while the expression of ATR3 was not able to reduce P450s in vitro (
;
;
). ATR1 expression plays a significant role in alkaloid synthesis in
Capsicum spp.
(
;
), and ATR2 is associated with the phenylpropanoid pathway and lignin biosynthesis in
Arabidopsis ( Mizutani and Ohta, 1998 )
. Similarly, the role of
WsCPR 2
in withanolide biosynthesis has been characterized in
Withania somnifera
(L.) Dunal (
). In
Gossypium hirsutum , GhCPR
2 is associated with defence responses, such as wounding and secondary metabolite biosynthesis (
). Metabolite production was markedly elevated when distinct CYP 450s were accompanied by different CPRs. Previous studies have reported that various plant CYP 450 proteins were accompanied by different CPRs, leading to 1422-fold and 946.5-fold increases in 1-oxo-Î²- amyrin and glycyrrhetinic acid levels, respectively, in
S. cerevisiae
compared to previous data (
). However, CYP 450 and CPR enzymes could not be efficiently expressed in prokaryotic cells such as
E. coli
as these enzymes are membrane anchored (
). Therefore, it is necessary to describe the function of CPRs in
S. grosvenorii
. Overall, transient expression is a particularly noteworthy method for developing a desirable approach to study gene function in
S. grosvenorii fruit
, which has been of interest in plant biochemical and molecular biological research on
S. grosvenorii
.

A previous study have suggested that CPRs are indispensable for CYP 450 expression (
), and in various plant species, the coexpression patterns of CYP 450s and CPRs have been estimated, including in
S. miltiorrhiza ( Guo et al., 2013 )
,
Papaver somniferum ( Rosco et al., 1997 )
and
A. thaliana ( Christ et al., 2013 )
. Generally, mammals harbour only one CPR (
), but one to four CPRs have been found in plants (
;
), making it more difficult to determine the function of each CPR. Moreover, numerous plant CYP 450s and CPRs have been previously identified and expressed in yeasts (
;
;
) and have rarely been reported in plant-associated prokaryotic species. Therefore, in our study, we first expressed SgCPRs in
S. grosvenorii
via a transient expression system. SgCPR expression levels were significantly increased or decreased in the PBI121- SgCPRs or pTRV- SgCPRs , respectively. The major metabolites mogrol, MIIE and MIII showed slight increases and decreases, respectively, although there was no increase in the SgCYP450 expression levels ( Figure S3 ). However, CPRs are the molecular chaperones for CYP 450, not the regulatory factors, so it was reasonable that the SgCYP450 expression levels remained unaffected. Notably, SgCPRs play pivotal roles in the mogroside biosynthesis pathway, which provides a novel approach for gene discovery in
S. grosvenorii
and will facilitate synthetic biological research on mogrosides.
